The translation of "Les maladies de la mondialisation" from French to English is "The diseases of globalization."
The globalization is being put to the severe test like never before.
His tensions simmer everywhere.
The vast majority of Sub-Saharan Africa, South America, the Middle East, and Central Asia is stagnating or struggling with an economic decline.
North America, Western Europe, and Japan are mired in slow growth and risk another recession.
The war now threatens in Iraq.
For proponents of open markets and free trade, this situation poses major challenges.
Why is globalization so threatened?
Why are its advantages apparently concentrated in a few places?
Can a more balanced globalization be implemented?
There is no simple answer to these questions.
Open markets are necessary for economic growth, but they barely suffice.
Certainly! The English translation of the given French sentence is:  "Certain regions of the world have benefited greatly from globalization, especially East Asia and China in recent years."
However, some regions have nonetheless derived meager benefits from this, particularly Sub-Saharan Africa.
The American government claims that poor countries are responsible for the majority of the problems they struggle with.
The slow growth of Africa, American leaders assert, is caused by the inadequacy of the African government.
However, life is more complicated than the Bush administration believes.
Let's consider the best-governed countries in Africa: Ghana, Tanzania, Malawi, and The Gambia.
Each of them has experienced a decline in living standards over the last two decades while a large number of Asian countries that ranked among the lowest in international comparisons of government performance (Pakistan, Bangladesh, Myanmar, and Sri Lanka) have experienced better economic growth.
It is true that economic performance is determined not only by governance standards, but also by geopolitics, geography, and economic structure.
The English translation of the given French sentence is:  "Countries with a large population and therefore large internal markets tend to grow more rapidly than countries with a small population."
(As with all trends of this kind, there are counterexamples).
The coastal countries tend to be more performing than landlocked countries.
The countries with high levels of malaria tend to experience slower growth than countries with lower levels of malaria.
Developing countries that border rich markets, such as Mexico, tend to be more performant than those that are far from the main markets.
These differences are of great importance.
If wealthy countries do not concern themselves with these structural problems, the gaps between winners and losers will continue to widen.
If wealthy countries shirk their responsibility by claiming that poorer nations are in some way culturally or politically unsuited to benefit from globalization, we will not only create deeper pockets of poverty but also intensify unrest.
This, in turn, will lead to increased levels of violence, hostile reactions, and terrorism.
It is therefore time to move to a more serious approach to globalization that the rich countries, and particularly America, do not offer.
This approach must start with the most urgent task, which is to address the fundamental needs of the poorest peoples in the world.
In some cases, their suffering can be alleviated mainly through better governance within their country.
But in others, an honest look at the gathered evidence will reveal that the main causes of poverty involve diseases, climate instability, poor soils, distances to markets, etc.
A honest assessment would go further to indicate that the poorest countries find themselves unable to raise sufficient funds to resolve such problems on their own.
Rather than seeing richer countries lecturing poorer ones about bad governance, real solutions require that richer countries offer sufficient financial assistance to overcome the most deeply rooted barriers.
A case will strikingly illustrate this situation.
The control of diseases requires a healthcare system capable of providing life-saving medications and basic preventive services such as bed nets to combat malaria and vitamins to fight nutritional deficiencies.
The system costs at least approximately 40 dollars per person and per year.
This sum represents merely a grain of sand for rich countries, which systematically spend over $2,000 per person and year on health, but it exceeds the capacity of poor countries like Malawi, which have annual per capita incomes of $200.
A functioning healthcare system would cost more than the entire revenue of its government!
Even if Malawi is well-governed, its population will die in large numbers from diseases until it receives adequate assistance.
The success of globalization requires that we think more like doctors and less like preachers.
Instead of reprimanding the poor for their "sins," we must offer prudent diagnoses, as any good doctor would do, for each country and each region, in order to understand the fundamental factors that hinder their growth and economic development.
In certain regions such as the Andes and Central Asia, the problem primarily stems from geographic isolation.
There, the task is to construct roads, air links, and Internet connectivity to help these remote regions establish productive links with the world.
The rich countries must contribute to the financing of these projects.
In Sub-Saharan Africa, the main challenges lie in disease control, soil fertility, and the development of educational opportunities.
Again, more foreign assistance is required.
In other regions, the main problems involve a lack of water, discrimination against women or other groups, or a variety of specific issues.
It is now time to take the complexities inherent to globalization seriously.
The ideology of a one-size-fits-all consensus from Washington is outdated.
On the eve of war, it is urgent to tackle the difficult task of ensuring that everyone benefits from globalization.
We can achieve this by removing the ideological blinkers from the wealthy and by mobilizing a partnership between the rich and the poor.
Our common future depends on it.
